Author: Moore, 1905
Critical Notes: Described from Japan; may not be present in the NEP.

Specimens from the NEP are likely to be mis-identified as this name is a holdover from when European literature dominated polychaete systematics. Northern European specimens have a distinct color pattern similar to our Cheilonereis cyclurus, which is very different from NEP worms identified as N. zonata.
Epigamia alexandri (Malmgren, 1867) describes a European species that is likely not present. What is known to be present is Epigamia magna.

(Myxicola sp.A sensu Leslie Harris, provisional name); In Europe, M. aesthetica is found on docks & hard-surfaces. However, specimens from the NEP that exhibit this habit are morphologically and genetically different. In the past, several species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, and Alaska. This material needs to be re-examined.

(Myxicola sp.B sensu Leslie Harris, provisional name); In Europe, M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments. However, specimens from the NEP that exhibit this habit are morphologically and genetically different. In the past, several species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, and Alaska. This material needs to be re-examined.

Author: Johnson, 1901
Critical Notes: Listed in older references as Serpula vermicularis which is a valid species but now restricted in range to Europe.

Author: Örsted, 1843
Critical Notes: Dodecaceria concharum is a European species which may not be present in the NEP; molecular analysis is required to confirm.

Author: Berkeley & Berkeley, 1954
Critical Notes: Dodecaceria fewkesi creates its own calcareous tube while D. concharum burrows into calcareous substrates.
More research is required to determine which species of Chaetopterus is present in the region.

Author: (Claparède, 1869)
Critical Notes: Reported as Spiochaetopterus costarum pottsi (Berkeley, 1927), an unaccepted infrataxon (WoRMS Editorial Board 2021).

PMLS records of Parasagitta elegans cannot be confirmed. Eukrohnia hamata Mijbius (1875) has been documented within the Salish Sea, where it occurs infrequently, being an oceanic species occasionally borne in by the intrusion of offshore waters
